[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Stage 2: Expert Discussion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Overlapping Concerns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The Architecture (A1, A2) and Security (S1) reviewers converge on operational safety: the recipe describes a system that could be deployed but lacks the monitoring and guardrails needed to detect when it's failing silently. A1 (no monitoring of safety constraint triggers) and A2 (no distribution shift detection) are two facets of the same gap: the system has no way to know when it's operating outside its competence boundary. S1 (flat IAM permissions) compounds this because a single compromised role could affect the entire pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The Architecture (A3) and Networking (N1) reviewers both identify under-specification in the serving layer: it's unclear whether the recipe recommends DynamoDB or SageMaker endpoints, and the VPC endpoints needed for SageMaker are missing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Priority Resolution
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - A1 and A2 are the highest-priority findings because they affect patient safety in a deployed system. A policy that silently degrades or operates on out-of-distribution patients without detection is dangerous. These are addressable with monitoring additions, not architectural redesign.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - S1 (IAM least-privilege) is HIGH because PHI is involved and the flat permission model is a compliance gap that auditors will flag.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The remaining issues are important for production readiness but do not affect the recipe's educational value or clinical correctness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Clinical Accuracy Assessment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The RL formulation is clinically appropriate:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Sepsis-3 criteria for cohort selection is current standard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - 4-hour time windows are standard in the literature
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The 5x5 action discretization (fluids x vasopressors) follows Komorowski et al.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Safety constraints are clinically reasonable (MAP < 55 requiring vasopressors, fluid overload limits, rising lactate contraindication)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The reward formulation options (terminal survival, intermediate SOFA) are well-established
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - CQL as the algorithm choice is appropriate for the distribution shift concern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The off-policy evaluation methodology (WIS + FQE + agreement rate) is the current best practice
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The "not production-ready" framing and regulatory pathway discussion are honest and accurate
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m One minor clinical note: Constraint 1 uses MAP < 55 as the threshold for requiring vasopressors. The Surviving Sepsis Campaign 2021 guidelines target MAP >= 65. A threshold of 55 is very permissive (allowing the policy to recommend no vasopressors for MAPs between 55-64). This is defensible as a "hard floor" (below which organ damage is near-certain) rather than a "target" (which is the clinician's job), but the distinction could be made explicit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
